{"cursor":"2155","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nThe 'coat of arms of [[Bermuda]]' depicts a red lion holding a shield that has a\ndepiction of a wrecked ship upon it. The red lion is a symbol of England and\nalludes to Bermudaâs relationship with that country. The wrecked ship is the\n[[Sea Venture]], the flagship of the Virginia Company. The ship was deliberately\ndriven on to the reefs of Bermuda, by Admiral Sir George Somers, in 1609, to\nprevent it from foundering in a storm. All aboard survived, resulting in the\nsettlement of the island. The Latin motto under the coat of arms, Quo Fata\nFerunt, means âWhither the Fates Carry [Us]â.\n\nIn the twentieth century, the coat of armsâwithout the banner holding the\nmottoâwas added to the Red ensign to create the distinguishing colonial flag\n(the national flag is the Union Jack, which appears in its upper, left corner),\nand on the Governor's Flag. The coat of arms features on the cover of the 1624\nedition of [[The Generall Historie of Virginia, New-England, and the Summer\nIsles]] (the Somers Isles is another name for Bermuda, commemorating Admiral\nSomers), by Captain John Smith.\n\nThe Bermuda old badge before 1910. The badge was based on a sketch, made in\n1869, of the 1817 seal, which depicted a wet dock of the time showing with some\nboats in the background. It is assumed that the scene alludes to the fact that\nthe islands were a stopover base for the sailing\nships http://www.rbvex.it/ameripag/bermuda.html when the badge was\napproved by the Admiralty.\n","linknr":304,"url":"Coat_of_Arms_of_Bermuda","recorded":1375081894,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Coat_of_arms_of_Bermuda&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Coat_of_arms_of_Bermuda&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Coat_of_arms_of_Bermu